        <div id="Major">
         <header class="tabheader">
          <h2>Major</h2>
         </header>
         <section class="acalog"> 
          <section id="367" class="requirements"> 
           <section class="core"> 
            <header>
             <h2>Requirements for the Major (44 credits)</h2>
            </header> 
            <p>20 upper-level credits are required.</p> 
            <section class="core"> 
             <header>
              <h3>I. Core (32 credits)</h3>
             </header> 
             <dl class="courses"> 
              <dt id="8440" data-termcode="" data-subjectcode="CHIN" data-coursenumber="350" data-credits="4" data-title="Selected Topics in Modern Chinese Literature and Film" class="">
                CHIN 350 - Selected Topics in Modern Chinese Literature and Film
              </dt> 
              <dd id="8440-d">
               <p>Chinese literature, cinema, and drama of the twentieth century, a time when China faced western challenges to its national identity and cultural tradition. Texts of the twentieth century are distinctively modern, covering such issues as westernization and tradition, revolution, family restructuring and women's role in society.</p>
               <p>Course may be repeated.</p>
               <p class="credits"><strong>Credits: </strong>4</p>
               <p class="gened"><strong>Attributes: </strong>CLA-Breadth/Humanities, CLA-Diversity International</p>
               <p class="offered"><strong>Offered: </strong>fall semester.</p>
              </dd> 
              <dt id="8950" data-termcode="" data-subjectcode="PSCI" data-coursenumber="228" data-credits="4" data-title="Chinese Politics" class="">
                PSCI 228 - Chinese Politics
              </dt> 
              <dd id="8950-d">
               <p>China, the world's largest country and one of the few remaining nominally communist nations, is undergoing unprecedented social, economic, and political chance. This course surveys China's contemporary political history, the reform movement, and China's transition from communism.</p>
               <p class="credits"><strong>Credits: </strong>4</p>
               <p class="gened"><strong>Attributes: </strong>CLA-Breadth/Social Science, CLA-Diversity International</p>
               <p class="offered"><strong>Offered: </strong>Annually.</p>
              </dd> 
              <dt id="8429" data-termcode="" data-subjectcode="CHIN" data-coursenumber="101" data-credits="4" data-title="Beginning Chinese I" class="">
                CHIN 101 - Beginning Chinese I
              </dt> 
              <dd id="8429-d">
               <p>An introduction to spoken and written Chinese. Language laboratory required.</p>
               <p class="credits"><strong>Credits: </strong>4</p>
               <p class="offered"><strong>Offered: </strong>fall semester.</p>
               <p><strong>Corequisite: </strong>CHIN 105.</p>
              </dd> 
              <dt id="8430" data-termcode="" data-subjectcode="CHIN" data-coursenumber="102" data-credits="4" data-title="Beginning Chinese II" class="">
                CHIN 102 - Beginning Chinese II
              </dt> 
              <dd id="8430-d">
               <p>An introduction to spoken and written Chinese. Language laboratory required.</p>
               <p class="credits"><strong>Credits: </strong>4</p>
               <p class="offered"><strong>Offered: </strong>spring semester.</p>
               <p><strong>Prerequisite: </strong>CHIN 101.</p>
               <p><strong>Corequisite: </strong>CHIN 106.</p>
              </dd> 
              <dt id="8433" data-termcode="" data-subjectcode="CHIN" data-coursenumber="201" data-credits="4" data-title="Intermediate Chinese I" class="">
                CHIN 201 - Intermediate Chinese I
              </dt> 
              <dd id="8433-d">
               <p>Intermediate spoken and written Chinese. Language laboratory required.</p>
               <p class="credits"><strong>Credits: </strong>4</p>
               <p class="gened"><strong>Attributes: </strong>CLA-Foreign Language</p>
               <p class="offered"><strong>Offered: </strong>fall semester.</p>
               <p><strong>Prerequisite: </strong>CHIN 102 or equivalent.</p>
              </dd> 
              <dt id="8435" data-termcode="" data-subjectcode="CHIN" data-coursenumber="202" data-credits="4" data-title="Intermediate Chinese II" class="">
                CHIN 202 - Intermediate Chinese II
              </dt> 
              <dd id="8435-d">
               <p>This course is designed for students who have completed Chinese 30 and intend to finish two years of language training. The course emphasizes speaking, vocabulary building, and the development of reading and translating skills. Teaching materials will include a textbook and newspaper/magazine articles.</p>
               <p class="credits"><strong>Credits: </strong>4</p>
               <p class="gened"><strong>Attributes: </strong>CLA-Foreign Language</p>
               <p class="offered"><strong>Offered: </strong>spring semester.</p>
               <p><strong>Prerequisite: </strong>CHIN 201 or equivalent.</p>
              </dd> 
              <dt id="8437" data-termcode="" data-subjectcode="CHIN" data-coursenumber="301" data-credits="4" data-title="Modern Chinese Society" class="">
                CHIN 301 - Modern Chinese Society
              </dt> 
              <dd id="8437-d">
               <p>Advanced training in listening comprehension and oral expression through study of modern Chinese society. Writing skills will be developed through critical essays on readings.</p>
               <p class="credits"><strong>Credits: </strong>4</p>
               <p class="gened"><strong>Attributes: </strong>CLA-Foreign Language</p>
               <p class="offered"><strong>Offered: </strong>fall semester in alternate years.</p>
              </dd> 
              <dt id="8438" data-termcode="" data-subjectcode="CHIN" data-coursenumber="310" data-credits="4" data-title="Advanced Chinese Reading" class="">
                CHIN 310 - Advanced Chinese Reading OR
              </dt> 
              <dd id="8438-d">
               <p>This is a second-semester course for the third-year of Chinese. It focuses on students' ability to read authentic Chinese texts. Other aspects of the language learning, such as speaking, character acquisition, writing and translation are also included.</p>
               <p class="credits"><strong>Credits: </strong>4</p>
               <p class="gened"><strong>Attributes: </strong>CLA-Writing Intensive</p>
               <p class="offered"><strong>Offered: </strong>every other sping semester.</p>
               <p><strong>Prerequisite: </strong>CHIN 301.</p>
              </dd> 
              <dt id="11852" data-termcode="" data-subjectcode="CHIN" data-coursenumber="311" data-credits="4" data-title="Advanced Chinese Translation" class="">
                CHIN 311 - Advanced Chinese Translation
              </dt> 
              <dd id="11852-d">
               <p class="credits"><strong>Credits: </strong>4</p>
               <p class="gened"><strong>Attributes: </strong>CLA- Writing Intensive</p>
               <p><strong>Prerequisite: </strong>CHIN 301 or other third-year language class.</p>
              </dd> 
              <dt id="8439" data-termcode="" data-subjectcode="CHIN" data-coursenumber="354" data-credits="4" data-title="Selected Topics in Classical Chinese Literature" class="">
                CHIN 354 - Selected Topics in Classical Chinese Literature
              </dt> 
              <dd id="8439-d">
               <p>Examination of the Chinese tradition in literature, culture and thought through critical study of classical texts in English translation. Subject matter may include selections from the genres of poetry, philosophical discourse, drama, tales, and the classical novel. Critical essay required of students.</p>
               <p>May be repeated for credit as topic varies.</p>
               <p class="credits"><strong>Credits: </strong>4</p>
               <p class="gened"><strong>Attributes: </strong>CLA-Capstone, CLA-Writing in the Major</p>
               <p class="offered"><strong>Offered: </strong>fall semester in even numbered years.</p>
              </dd> 
             </dl> 
             <section class="core"> 
              <header>
               <h4>Note</h4>
              </header> 
              <p>CHIN 101 and CHIN 102 may be exempted through a placement exam. If exempted, a corresponding number of credits (4 or 8) must be completed from CHIN 250, CHIN 354, CHIN 350, or the Drew Summer language program, and/or the approved study-abroad language programs.</p> 
             </section> 
            </section> 
            <section class="core"> 
             <header>
              <h3>II. Electives (12 credits)</h3>
             </header> 
             <dl class="courses"> 
              <dt id="8434" data-termcode="" data-subjectcode="CHIN" data-coursenumber="250" data-credits="4" data-title="Topics in Chinese Culture" class="">
                CHIN 250 - Topics in Chinese Culture
              </dt> 
              <dd id="8434-d">
               <p>An interdisciplinary and comparative introduction to important elements of both traditional and modern Chinese culture, including history, language, literature, art, philosophy/religion, family/marriage, and science/technology/medicine.</p>
               <p>Course may be repeated.</p>
               <p class="credits"><strong>Credits: </strong>4</p>
               <p class="gened"><strong>Attributes: </strong>CLA-Breadth/Interdisciplinary, CLA-Diversity International</p>
               <p class="offered"><strong>Offered: </strong>spring semester in even-numbered years.</p>
              </dd> 
              <dt id="8437" data-termcode="" data-subjectcode="CHIN" data-coursenumber="301" data-credits="4" data-title="Modern Chinese Society" class="">
                CHIN 301 - Modern Chinese Society OR
              </dt> 
              <dd id="8437-d">
               <p>Advanced training in listening comprehension and oral expression through study of modern Chinese society. Writing skills will be developed through critical essays on readings.</p>
               <p class="credits"><strong>Credits: </strong>4</p>
               <p class="gened"><strong>Attributes: </strong>CLA-Foreign Language</p>
               <p class="offered"><strong>Offered: </strong>fall semester in alternate years.</p>
              </dd> 
              <dt id="8438" data-termcode="" data-subjectcode="CHIN" data-coursenumber="310" data-credits="4" data-title="Advanced Chinese Reading" class="">
                CHIN 310 - Advanced Chinese Reading OR
              </dt> 
              <dd id="8438-d">
               <p>This is a second-semester course for the third-year of Chinese. It focuses on students' ability to read authentic Chinese texts. Other aspects of the language learning, such as speaking, character acquisition, writing and translation are also included.</p>
               <p class="credits"><strong>Credits: </strong>4</p>
               <p class="gened"><strong>Attributes: </strong>CLA-Writing Intensive</p>
               <p class="offered"><strong>Offered: </strong>every other sping semester.</p>
               <p><strong>Prerequisite: </strong>CHIN 301.</p>
              </dd> 
              <dt id="11852" data-termcode="" data-subjectcode="CHIN" data-coursenumber="311" data-credits="4" data-title="Advanced Chinese Translation" class="">
                CHIN 311 - Advanced Chinese Translation
              </dt> 
              <dd id="11852-d">
               <p class="credits"><strong>Credits: </strong>4</p>
               <p class="gened"><strong>Attributes: </strong>CLA- Writing Intensive</p>
               <p><strong>Prerequisite: </strong>CHIN 301 or other third-year language class.</p>
              </dd> 
              <dt id="8440" data-termcode="" data-subjectcode="CHIN" data-coursenumber="350" data-credits="4" data-title="Selected Topics in Modern Chinese Literature and Film" class="">
                CHIN 350 - Selected Topics in Modern Chinese Literature and Film (can be repeated for credit if the topic is different than course taken from section I)
              </dt> 
              <dd id="8440-d">
               <p>Chinese literature, cinema, and drama of the twentieth century, a time when China faced western challenges to its national identity and cultural tradition. Texts of the twentieth century are distinctively modern, covering such issues as westernization and tradition, revolution, family restructuring and women's role in society.</p>
               <p>Course may be repeated.</p>
               <p class="credits"><strong>Credits: </strong>4</p>
               <p class="gened"><strong>Attributes: </strong>CLA-Breadth/Humanities, CLA-Diversity International</p>
               <p class="offered"><strong>Offered: </strong>fall semester.</p>
              </dd> 
              <dt id="8335" data-termcode="" data-subjectcode="ARTH" data-coursenumber="312" data-credits="4" data-title="Arts of Asia" class="">
                ARTH 312 - Arts of Asia (when on East Asia or China)
              </dt> 
              <dd id="8335-d">
               <p>This course focuses on a special theme or period in Asian art, such as Chinese traditions and their modern expressions, the East Asian nature traditions, and arts of India.</p>
               <p>Course may be repeated.</p>
               <p class="credits"><strong>Credits: </strong>4</p>
               <p class="offered"><strong>Offered: </strong>spring semester in even-numbered years.</p>
              </dd> 
              <dt id="8444" data-termcode="" data-subjectcode="CHIN" data-coursenumber="281" data-credits="4" data-title="Intermediate Intensive Speaking Chinese" class="">
                CHIN 281 - Intermediate Intensive Speaking Chinese (study abroad)
              </dt> 
              <dd id="8444-d">
               <p>An intensive course in spoken Mandarin. Drills and exercises on pronunciation, intonation, and prosody of Standard Mandarin (putonghua). Intermediate sentence patterns and grammar, vocabulary, and idiomatic expressions of spoken Chinese. Maximum enrollment of five students per section. Five 120-minute classes weekly for four weeks. Conducted in Chinese.</p>
               <p class="credits"><strong>Credits: </strong>4</p>
               <p class="gened"><strong>Attributes: </strong>CLA-Off Campus Experience</p>
               <p><strong>Prerequisite: </strong>CHIN 102.</p>
              </dd> 
              <dt id="8445" data-termcode="" data-subjectcode="CHIN" data-coursenumber="282" data-credits="4" data-title="Intensive Chinese: Listening and Understanding" class="">
                CHIN 282 - Intensive Chinese: Listening and Understanding (study abroad)
              </dt> 
              <dd id="8445-d">
               <p>An intensive course in the comprehension of Mandarin. Listening drills will feature situational Chinese spoken at a natural pace, both with and without regional accents. Some listening exercises will use popular and traditional songs, public announcements, radio and television broadcasts. Maximum enrollment of five students per section. Five 120-minute classes weekly for four weeks. Conducted Mostly in Chinese.</p>
               <p class="credits"><strong>Credits: </strong>4</p>
               <p class="gened"><strong>Attributes: </strong>CLA-Off Campus Experience</p>
               <p><strong>Prerequisite: </strong>CHIN 102.</p>
              </dd> 
              <dt id="8441" data-termcode="" data-subjectcode="CHIN" data-coursenumber="300" data-credits="2-4" data-title="Independent Study in Chinese" class="">
                CHIN 300 - Independent Study in Chinese
              </dt> 
              <dd id="8441-d">
               <p>A course for students who wish to continue the study of Chinese at an advanced level.</p>
               <p>Signature of instructor required for registration.</p>
               <p>Course may be repeated.</p>
               <p class="credits"><strong>Credits: </strong>2-4</p>
               <p class="gened"><strong>Attributes: </strong>CLA-Foreign Language</p>
               <p class="offered"><strong>Offered: </strong>every semester.</p>
              </dd> 
              <dt id="11851" data-termcode="" data-subjectcode="CHIN" data-coursenumber="302" data-credits="4" data-title="Classical Chinese Culture" class="">
                CHIN 302 - Classical Chinese Culture
              </dt> 
              <dd id="11851-d">
               <p>May be repeated once with the permission of the instructor.</p>
               <p class="credits"><strong>Credits: </strong>4</p>
               <p class="offered"><strong>Offered: </strong>fall semester in alternate years.</p>
               <p><strong>Prerequisite: </strong>CHIN 202 or higher.</p>
              </dd> 
              <dt id="8442" data-termcode="" data-subjectcode="CHIN" data-coursenumber="381" data-credits="4" data-title="Advanced Intensive Speaking Chinese" class="">
                CHIN 381 - Advanced Intensive Speaking Chinese (study abroad)
              </dt> 
              <dd id="8442-d">
               <p>An intensive course in spoken Mandarin. Drills and exercises on pronunciation, intonation, and prosody of Standard Mandarin (putonghua). Advanced sentence patterns and grammar, vocabulary, and idiomatic expressions of spoken Chinese. Maximum enrollment of five students per section. Five 120-minute classes weekly for four weeks. Conducted in Chinese.</p>
               <p class="credits"><strong>Credits: </strong>4</p>
               <p class="gened"><strong>Attributes: </strong>CLA-Off Campus Experience</p>
               <p><strong>Prerequisite: </strong>CHIN+100.</p>
              </dd> 
              <dt id="8443" data-termcode="" data-subjectcode="CHIN" data-coursenumber="382" data-credits="4" data-title="Intensive Chinese: Listening and Understanding" class="">
                CHIN 382 - Intensive Chinese: Listening and Understanding (study abroad)
              </dt> 
              <dd id="8443-d">
               <p>An intensive course in the comprehension of Mandarin. Listening drills will feature situational Chinese spoken at a natural pace, both with and without regional accents. Some listening exercises will use popular and traditional songs, public announcements, radio and television broadcasts. Maximum enrollment of five students per section. Five 120-minute classes weekly for four weeks. Conducted in Chinese.</p>
               <p class="credits"><strong>Credits: </strong>4</p>
               <p class="gened"><strong>Attributes: </strong>CLA-Off Campus Experience</p>
               <p><strong>Prerequisite: </strong>CHIN+100.</p>
              </dd> 
              <dt id="8494" data-termcode="" data-subjectcode="ECON" data-coursenumber="250" data-credits="2-4" data-title="Selected Topics in Economics" class="">
                ECON 250 - Selected Topics in Economics (when appropriate)
              </dt> 
              <dd id="8494-d">
               <p>Recent topics have included the economics of food and nutrition, the economics of corporate downsizing, and the economics of financial market integration and comparative central banking.</p>
               <p>May be repeated for credit as topic changes.</p>
               <p class="credits"><strong>Credits: </strong>2-4</p>
               <p class="offered"><strong>Offered: </strong>Offering to be determined.</p>
               <p><strong>Prerequisite: </strong>ECON 101 (and ECON 102 when topic merits it; see course listings each semester).</p>
              </dd> 
              <dt id="8693" data-termcode="" data-subjectcode="HIST" data-coursenumber="264" data-credits="4" data-title="Modern China: From Opium Wars to the World" s="" workshop'="" class="">
                HIST 264 - Modern China: From Opium Wars to the World's Workshop
              </dt> 
              <dd id="8693-d">
               <p>This course examines political, cultural and economic transformations in China from the 19th century to the present. Covering the Opium Wars, the Taiping Rebellion, the collapse of the Qing Dynasty, Civil War, the Communist Revolution, the Cold War, globalization and China's rise at the end of the 20th century to become the world's workshop, this course will explore what has been for China the most tumultuous and arguably the most transformative century of its nearly four thousand year existence.</p>
               <p class="credits"><strong>Credits: </strong>4</p>
               <p class="gened"><strong>Attributes: </strong>CLA-Breadth/Humanities, CLA-Diversity International</p>
               <p class="offered"><strong>Offered: </strong>To be Determined.</p>
              </dd> 
              <dt id="9061" data-termcode="" data-subjectcode="REL" data-coursenumber="270" data-credits="4" data-title="East Asia: Tradition and Today" class="">
                REL 270 - East Asia: Tradition and Today
              </dt> 
              <dd id="9061-d">
               <p>The course analyzes religion as cultural traditions that have influentially defined the East Asian region across the centuries and up to the present, largely through a consideration of literature, arts and practices of China and Japan. Thematic topics include social definitions of community, traditional depictions of status according to class and gender, and the creation of paths of ethical behavior that promote social cohesion. We will explore these themes through historical interactions among traditions as well as challenges to and the use of tradition in the present day. The course includes field trips to Japanese traditional institutions devoted to the practice of Zen and the Way of Tea (Chado) in New York City.</p>
               <p class="credits"><strong>Credits: </strong>4</p>
               <p class="gened"><strong>Attributes: </strong>CLA-Breadth/Humanities, CLA-Diversity International</p>
               <p class="offered"><strong>Offered: </strong>spring semester.</p>
              </dd> 
             </dl> 
            </section> 
            <section class="core"> 
             <header>
              <h3>Note</h3>
             </header> 
             <p>Study abroad in a Drew or Drew-approved program is strongly recommended, especially for students who wish to emphasize language. With prior approval from the program director, students may replace up to 16 credits with courses completed in such programs: 4 language credits in the Core and 12 elective credits.</p> 
            </section> 
           </section> 
          </section>
         </section>
        </div>
        <div id="Minor">
         <header class="tabheader">
          <h2>Minor</h2>
         </header>
         <section class="acalog"> 
          <section id="368" class="requirements"> 
           <section class="core"> 
            <header>
             <h2>Requirements for the Minor (26 credits)</h2>
            </header> 
            <section class="core"> 
             <header>
              <h3>I. Core (18 credits)</h3>
             </header> 
             <dl class="courses"> 
              <dt id="8430" data-termcode="" data-subjectcode="CHIN" data-coursenumber="102" data-credits="4" data-title="Beginning Chinese II" class="">
                CHIN 102 - Beginning Chinese II
              </dt> 
              <dd id="8430-d">
               <p>An introduction to spoken and written Chinese. Language laboratory required.</p>
               <p class="credits"><strong>Credits: </strong>4</p>
               <p class="offered"><strong>Offered: </strong>spring semester.</p>
               <p><strong>Prerequisite: </strong>CHIN 101.</p>
               <p><strong>Corequisite: </strong>CHIN 106.</p>
              </dd> 
              <dt id="8433" data-termcode="" data-subjectcode="CHIN" data-coursenumber="201" data-credits="4" data-title="Intermediate Chinese I" class="">
                CHIN 201 - Intermediate Chinese I
              </dt> 
              <dd id="8433-d">
               <p>Intermediate spoken and written Chinese. Language laboratory required.</p>
               <p class="credits"><strong>Credits: </strong>4</p>
               <p class="gened"><strong>Attributes: </strong>CLA-Foreign Language</p>
               <p class="offered"><strong>Offered: </strong>fall semester.</p>
               <p><strong>Prerequisite: </strong>CHIN 102 or equivalent.</p>
              </dd> 
              <dt id="8435" data-termcode="" data-subjectcode="CHIN" data-coursenumber="202" data-credits="4" data-title="Intermediate Chinese II" class="">
                CHIN 202 - Intermediate Chinese II
              </dt> 
              <dd id="8435-d">
               <p>This course is designed for students who have completed Chinese 30 and intend to finish two years of language training. The course emphasizes speaking, vocabulary building, and the development of reading and translating skills. Teaching materials will include a textbook and newspaper/magazine articles.</p>
               <p class="credits"><strong>Credits: </strong>4</p>
               <p class="gened"><strong>Attributes: </strong>CLA-Foreign Language</p>
               <p class="offered"><strong>Offered: </strong>spring semester.</p>
               <p><strong>Prerequisite: </strong>CHIN 201 or equivalent.</p>
              </dd> 
              <dt id="8440" data-termcode="" data-subjectcode="CHIN" data-coursenumber="350" data-credits="4" data-title="Selected Topics in Modern Chinese Literature and Film" class="">
                CHIN 350 - Selected Topics in Modern Chinese Literature and Film
              </dt> 
              <dd id="8440-d">
               <p>Chinese literature, cinema, and drama of the twentieth century, a time when China faced western challenges to its national identity and cultural tradition. Texts of the twentieth century are distinctively modern, covering such issues as westernization and tradition, revolution, family restructuring and women's role in society.</p>
               <p>Course may be repeated.</p>
               <p class="credits"><strong>Credits: </strong>4</p>
               <p class="gened"><strong>Attributes: </strong>CLA-Breadth/Humanities, CLA-Diversity International</p>
               <p class="offered"><strong>Offered: </strong>fall semester.</p>
              </dd> 
              <dt id="8432" data-termcode="" data-subjectcode="CHIN" data-coursenumber="106" data-credits="2" data-title="Introduction to Chinese Character Writing II" class="">
                CHIN 106 - Introduction to Chinese Character Writing II
              </dt> 
              <dd id="8432-d">
               <p>Chinese character-based exercise session to facilitate CHIN 102.</p>
               <p class="credits"><strong>Credits: </strong>2</p>
               <p><strong>Corequisite: </strong>CHIN 102.</p>
              </dd> 
             </dl> 
            </section> 
            <section class="core"> 
             <header>
              <h3>II. Additional (8 credits)</h3>
             </header> 
             <dl class="courses"> 
              <dt id="8335" data-termcode="" data-subjectcode="ARTH" data-coursenumber="312" data-credits="4" data-title="Arts of Asia" class="">
                ARTH 312 - Arts of Asia
              </dt> 
              <dd id="8335-d">
               <p>This course focuses on a special theme or period in Asian art, such as Chinese traditions and their modern expressions, the East Asian nature traditions, and arts of India.</p>
               <p>Course may be repeated.</p>
               <p class="credits"><strong>Credits: </strong>4</p>
               <p class="offered"><strong>Offered: </strong>spring semester in even-numbered years.</p>
              </dd> 
              <dt id="8434" data-termcode="" data-subjectcode="CHIN" data-coursenumber="250" data-credits="4" data-title="Topics in Chinese Culture" class="">
                CHIN 250 - Topics in Chinese Culture
              </dt> 
              <dd id="8434-d">
               <p>An interdisciplinary and comparative introduction to important elements of both traditional and modern Chinese culture, including history, language, literature, art, philosophy/religion, family/marriage, and science/technology/medicine.</p>
               <p>Course may be repeated.</p>
               <p class="credits"><strong>Credits: </strong>4</p>
               <p class="gened"><strong>Attributes: </strong>CLA-Breadth/Interdisciplinary, CLA-Diversity International</p>
               <p class="offered"><strong>Offered: </strong>spring semester in even-numbered years.</p>
              </dd> 
              <dt id="8437" data-termcode="" data-subjectcode="CHIN" data-coursenumber="301" data-credits="4" data-title="Modern Chinese Society" class="">
                CHIN 301 - Modern Chinese Society
              </dt> 
              <dd id="8437-d">
               <p>Advanced training in listening comprehension and oral expression through study of modern Chinese society. Writing skills will be developed through critical essays on readings.</p>
               <p class="credits"><strong>Credits: </strong>4</p>
               <p class="gened"><strong>Attributes: </strong>CLA-Foreign Language</p>
               <p class="offered"><strong>Offered: </strong>fall semester in alternate years.</p>
              </dd> 
              <dt id="8439" data-termcode="" data-subjectcode="CHIN" data-coursenumber="354" data-credits="4" data-title="Selected Topics in Classical Chinese Literature" class="">
                CHIN 354 - Selected Topics in Classical Chinese Literature
              </dt> 
              <dd id="8439-d">
               <p>Examination of the Chinese tradition in literature, culture and thought through critical study of classical texts in English translation. Subject matter may include selections from the genres of poetry, philosophical discourse, drama, tales, and the classical novel. Critical essay required of students.</p>
               <p>May be repeated for credit as topic varies.</p>
               <p class="credits"><strong>Credits: </strong>4</p>
               <p class="gened"><strong>Attributes: </strong>CLA-Capstone, CLA-Writing in the Major</p>
               <p class="offered"><strong>Offered: </strong>fall semester in even numbered years.</p>
              </dd> 
              <dt id="8950" data-termcode="" data-subjectcode="PSCI" data-coursenumber="228" data-credits="4" data-title="Chinese Politics" class="">
                PSCI 228 - Chinese Politics
              </dt> 
              <dd id="8950-d">
               <p>China, the world's largest country and one of the few remaining nominally communist nations, is undergoing unprecedented social, economic, and political chance. This course surveys China's contemporary political history, the reform movement, and China's transition from communism.</p>
               <p class="credits"><strong>Credits: </strong>4</p>
               <p class="gened"><strong>Attributes: </strong>CLA-Breadth/Social Science, CLA-Diversity International</p>
               <p class="offered"><strong>Offered: </strong>Annually.</p>
              </dd> 
              <dt id="9061" data-termcode="" data-subjectcode="REL" data-coursenumber="270" data-credits="4" data-title="East Asia: Tradition and Today" class="">
                REL 270 - East Asia: Tradition and Today
              </dt> 
              <dd id="9061-d">
               <p>The course analyzes religion as cultural traditions that have influentially defined the East Asian region across the centuries and up to the present, largely through a consideration of literature, arts and practices of China and Japan. Thematic topics include social definitions of community, traditional depictions of status according to class and gender, and the creation of paths of ethical behavior that promote social cohesion. We will explore these themes through historical interactions among traditions as well as challenges to and the use of tradition in the present day. The course includes field trips to Japanese traditional institutions devoted to the practice of Zen and the Way of Tea (Chado) in New York City.</p>
               <p class="credits"><strong>Credits: </strong>4</p>
               <p class="gened"><strong>Attributes: </strong>CLA-Breadth/Humanities, CLA-Diversity International</p>
               <p class="offered"><strong>Offered: </strong>spring semester.</p>
              </dd> 
              <dt id="8344" data-termcode="" data-subjectcode="ASST" data-coursenumber="223" data-credits="2-4" data-title="Selected Topics in Asian Studies" class="">
                ASST 223 - Selected Topics in Asian Studies (when topic is East Asia)
              </dt> 
              <dd id="8344-d">
               <p>This course permits offering of various topics in Asian Studies which are not available on a regular basis. The course will often reflect some special interest of the person teaching it.</p>
               <p>May be repeated for credit as topic changes.</p>
               <p class="credits"><strong>Credits: </strong>2-4</p>
               <p class="offered"><strong>Offered: </strong>Offering varies.</p>
              </dd> 
             </dl> 
            </section> 
           </section> 
          </section>
         </section>
        </div>
       </div> 
